box.text: Abstracted audio replay into slideraudio patcher.
Simplified stimulus toggle by using matrixctrl.
Simplified patch by using scripting to interact with GUI objects.
Main DAC module for patch receiving left and right signals from all sfplay functions. Receives play and stop commands from the Play Control module

This module controls the playback of the patch. Instructions are received from the play/pause button. Pressing the space bar or pressing "Play/Pause" will start or pause the audio. Pressing "Stop" or s will stop the audio. The Sync bang is sent to each channel to synchronise the audio and restart it from the beginning. The audio is stopped and re-synced at the end of each page
This module returns the audio for each slider. The audio is replayed from a separate patcher: slideraudio. Double-click the slideraudio object to open the patcher.

The numbers above choose a column in this matrixctrl to turn on. The matrixctrl ensure only 1 option is selected per row. It outputs all changes as [column row value], where value is 0 for off and 1 for on. The row can be ignored. These values can be sent directly to the audio faders to open or close them. With some processing the value can be sent to "Scale Score Locking" in order to  control the gates that either pass the slider value or short-circuit it. Lastly, the buttons must also be set, which is again done directly using the value parameter.
This module selects the stimulus: changes the audio faders, the buttons, and locks/unlocks the appropriate sliders.
Add or remove [select] outputs in "Audio Bank Selector" according to numbank
Add or remove [select] outputs in "Stimulus Chooser" according to numproc

This module determines the number of stimuli to be auditioned. The patch will need to be reloaded for any changes to take effect. Modifying these numbers will further require changes to "Stimulus Chooser" and "Audio Bank Selector"
Number of music tracks (i.e. how many banks)
Write audio filenames here (no spaces). Store all audio files in the "Stimuli" subdirectory of the patch folder since this is set as the search path in the module 'Set Search Path'

This module selects the bank of audio for the current page. A new bank is chosen at the start of each page. The filenames are sent to 'Audio File Assignment' where the stimuli are randomly assigned to each button.
This module controls the loading of the patch. Most modules must be initiated before the patch can be used. This initiation must happen in a particular order. This module controls the order.

This module chooses the stimulus to compare to the reference. A number of stimuli may be specified;the module will repeat the presentation of each stimulus the specified number of times. The number of pages is equal to the number of stimuli multiplied by the number of repeats. The module generates a random number corresponding to the stimulus. Hence, the order of presentation is randomised. The module counts how many times each number is generated so that each stimulus is played for no more than the specified number of repeats. The chosen file is sent to the 'Audio file asignment' module.
if $i1<=$i2 then set Page $i1 of $i2 else set Page $i2 of $i2

This module packs the score (1 for correct, 0 for incorrect), the correct answer (1 for A, 2 for B) with the corresponding stimulus file name. The results are then written to a csv file - this happens automatically every page and is presented at the end of the test.
This section of the module automatically saves a time-stamped backup of the data after each page is completed
Number of processes (i.e. how many tracks in each bank)
This module controls the pages, i.e. the displayed page number.
This module controls the reset of the page after it is reset. It also clears 'Text' in 'Export Results' at the end of the last page
This module randomly assigns the stimulus and reference to each button. "urn" generates the random sequence serially and "cycle" assigns them to each button.

This module sets the search path of the patch as the folder (and all subfolders) in which the patch is contained. This path is also used by the automatic backup feature and is hence the location in which automatic backups are stored.
